Let $\theta = \arcsin \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}}.$  Then $\sin \theta = \frac{3}{\sqrt{10}},$ so $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = (1,0);
C = intersectionpoint(arc(O,1,0,90),arc(A,sqrt(10),0,180));

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(Circle(A,sqrt(10)));
draw(O--C--A);

label("$\theta$", (0.2,0.1));
label("$\frac{3}{\sqrt{10}}$", (C + A)/2, S);
label("$\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}$", (C + O)/2, W);
[/asy]

Then
\[\arctan x = \theta - \arccos \frac{y}{\sqrt{1 + y^2}}.\]Let $\alpha = \arctan x.$  Then $\tan \alpha = x,$ so
\[\cos \alpha = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 + x^2}} \quad \text{and} \quad \sin \alpha = \frac{x}{\sqrt{1 + x^2}}.\]Let $\beta = \arccos \frac{y}{\sqrt{1 + y^2}}.$  Then $\cos \beta = \frac{y}{\sqrt{1 + y^2}},$ so
\[\sin \beta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 + y^2}}.\]Hence,
\[\cos (\theta - \beta) = \cos \theta \cos \beta + \sin \theta \sin \beta = \frac{y}{\sqrt{10} \sqrt{1 + y^2}} + \frac{3}{\sqrt{10} \sqrt{1 + y^2}} = \frac{y + 3}{\sqrt{10} \sqrt{1 + y^2}}.\]Also,
\[\cos (\theta - \beta) = \cos \alpha = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 + x^2}}.\]Thus,
\[\frac{y + 3}{\sqrt{10} \sqrt{1 + y^2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1 + x^2}}.\]Then $(y + 3)^2 (1 + x^2) = 10(1 + y^2),$ which expands as
\[x^2 y^2 + 6xy + 9x^2 + y^2 - 7 = 0.\]Final Answer: $\boxed{(9,6,-7)}.$

